data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Inventory of issues in your code

| Line | API | Problem on .NET 8 |
|------|-----|--------------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `Thread.Abort` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — cleanup logic silently lost |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `Thread.ResetAbort` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Pattern classification

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `ProcessLoop` while-loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| ThreadAbortException as control flow | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Thread.ResetAbort to continue | `ResetAbort()` inside catch | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide |
| Timeout enforcement | `Stop()` — wait 2s then abort | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` or `Task.Wait` with timeout |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work, then exit cleanly
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces Thread.ResetAbort + loop re-check)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. Unlike Thread.Abort, there is NO
            // forcible kill in modern .NET. Log a warning — see pitfalls below.
            Console.Error.WriteLine(
                "WARNING: Worker thread did not exit within 2 seconds after cancellation.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O); a bare bool cannot unblock a sleeping/waiting thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard prevents swallowing unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No auto-rethrow to suppress; just exit the loop |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then check | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | `Join` actually waits for the thread to finish — `Sleep` was a race condition |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` holds timer/callback resources that must be released |

### Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem()` must cooperate

This is the **#1 migration failure point**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous call (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take()`, `socket.Receive()`, `Console.ReadLine()`), cancelling the token does nothing — the thread stays blocked forever.

You must thread the token through to the blocking call:

```csharp
// ❌ BROKEN — cancellation cannot interrupt this
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ FIXED — throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
var item = queue.Take(token);

// ✅ FIXED — for I/O, use async + token
var item = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token);

// ✅ FIXED — for WaitHandle-based blocking
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
```

### Additional pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact | Fix |
|---------|--------|-----|
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | `ProcessItem` does expensive work but never checks for cancellation — thread hangs until the item finishes | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` |
| **No forcible kill exists** | If uncooperative code never checks the token, `Stop()` cannot force termination | Move uncooperative work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Timer and callback leaks | Implement `IDisposable` (shown above) |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Masks bugs where a different `CancellationToken` was cancelled unexpectedly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard |
| **`finally` behavior difference** | In .NET Framework, `Thread.Abort` would re-raise after the catch; `finally` ran during unwind. In .NET 8, the `break` exits normally — `finally` still runs, but the *control flow path* is different | Verify `FlushBuffers()` is safe to call in both normal-exit and cancellation-exit paths |

### Verification checklist

- [ ] No references to `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`
- [ ] No `SYSLIB0006` warnings
- [ ] `GetNextItem` accepts and honors the `CancellationToken`
- [ ] `ProcessItem` checks `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals
- [ ] `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed
- [ ] `Stop()` logs or handles the case where the thread doesn't exit in time
- [ ] Existing tests updated to cancel via `CancellationTokenSource` instead of relying on `Thread.Abort`
